const e="assignment-exercise",o="Assignment & Exercise (What Happens at Expiration)",t="7 min",s=[{screen_type:"hook",visual:"üì¨‚ö†Ô∏è",headline:"Friday 4pm: Your broker just assigned you 100 shares",text:"You thought your option would just expire. Instead, you wake up Monday owning $25,000 of stock you didn't plan to buy. This happens to beginners who don't understand assignment. Let's make sure it never surprises you."},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"Exercise vs Assignment",text:"EXERCISE = YOU decide to use your option (buy or sell shares at strike). ASSIGNMENT = SOMEONE ELSE exercised and YOU'RE on the hook to deliver shares. Happens automatically if your option is ITM at expiration. Most traders SELL options before expiration to avoid this.",visual:"üîÑ",highlight_words:["EXERCISE","YOU decide","ASSIGNMENT","on the hook","ITM at expiration"]},{screen_type:"key_terms",headline:"Assignment & Exercise Terms",cards:[{term:"Exercise",definition:"Using your option to buy/sell shares at strike price",example:"You own $100 call, stock at $120. Exercise = buy 100 shares at $100 (pay $10,000). Most traders SELL the option instead for cash."},{term:"Assignment",definition:"Being forced to fulfill the obligation of an option you SOLD",example:"You sold a call. Someone exercised. You MUST deliver 100 shares at strike price. This is why beginners should only BUY options initially."},{term:"Automatic Exercise",definition:"Broker auto-exercises ITM options at expiration",example:"Friday 4pm: You own $100 call, stock at $105. You forgot to sell it. Your broker exercises it automatically. Monday: you own 100 shares."}]},{screen_type:"analogy",headline:"Think of it like a concert ticket voucher",text:"You have a voucher for concert tickets at $50 each (your call option). The actual ticket price is now $200. You have three choices on the deadline day...",interactive:"tap_to_reveal",reveal_sections:[{label:"SELL the voucher to someone else",content:"Your voucher is worth $150 ($200 - $50). Sell it for cash, never deal with actual tickets. This is what 95% of option traders do - SELL the option for profit."},{label:"EXERCISE: Use voucher to buy tickets",content:"Pay $50, get tickets worth $200. Now you own tickets (must sell separately). Complicated. Only do this if you WANT to own the actual asset (shares)."},{label:"EXPIRE: Let voucher expire",content:"If tickets are $40 and your voucher is for $50, it's worthless. Let it expire. You lose the voucher cost, but you don't buy overpriced tickets."},{label:"This is how options work",content:"SELL = get cash, easiest (most common). EXERCISE = get shares, complicated. EXPIRE = option worthless, lose premium."}]},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"It's expiration Friday at 3:55pm. Your call is ITM by $10. What should you do?",options:["Let it expire and collect profit automatically","Exercise it to get shares","SELL the option before 4pm to get cash","Do nothing - the broker handles it"],correct:2,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Smart! Selling the option converts your profit to CASH instantly. No need to deal with shares, margin, or settlement. Exercise only if you WANT to own shares. 95% of option traders sell rather than exercise.",explanation_wrong:"If you do nothing, your broker will AUTO-EXERCISE at 4pm (if ITM). Monday morning, you'll own 100 shares = need $10,000+ in your account. Avoid this surprise! SELL the option for immediate cash profit before 4pm."},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"You SOLD a covered call. Stock rocketed above your strike. What might happen?",options:["Nothing - you keep your shares","You might get assigned - forced to sell shares at strike","You have to buy back the call","Assignment only happens to buyers"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Exactly! When you SELL options, you take on the OBLIGATION. If the buyer exercises, you're ASSIGNED. For covered calls, you must sell your 100 shares at the strike price. This is expected and OK - but beginners should understand this risk.",explanation_wrong:"When you SELL (not buy) options, you can be ASSIGNED. The buyer exercises their right, you fulfill the obligation. For covered calls, this means selling your shares at the strike. Often fine, but you need to understand it can happen anytime."},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"Monday morning: Your account shows you own 100 shares of TSLA ($25,000 worth). You didn't buy them. What happened?",options:["Your broker made an error","Your ITM call was auto-exercised over the weekend","You were hacked","This is impossible"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Bingo! Friday 4pm: Your call was ITM. Your broker exercised it automatically. Saturday: Settlement processes. Monday: Shares appear in your account. If you don't have $25k cash, you're now on margin (borrowing). This is why you SELL before expiration!",explanation_wrong:"This is the 'surprise assignment' many beginners experience. Your ITM call was exercised automatically by your broker at expiration. Now you own shares. If you don't have the cash, you're on margin (borrowing) and paying interest. Avoid this: SELL the option before 4pm Friday!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"Your put is ITM by $5 at expiration. You don't own the underlying stock. What happens if you don't sell the put?",options:["Nothing - it expires worthless","You get $500 cash","You're forced to SHORT 100 shares (advanced, risky)","Your broker cancels it"],correct:2,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Danger zone! Your put gives you the RIGHT to SELL shares at strike. But you don't own them. If exercised, you SHORT 100 shares = huge risk. Your broker may prevent this or force you to buy shares first. ALWAYS sell ITM puts before expiration if you don't own stock!",explanation_wrong:"ITM put at expiration without owning shares = your broker might: 1) Auto-exercise and SHORT shares (risky), 2) Sell the put automatically, or 3) Close your position. Every broker differs. Don't risk it - SELL the put before 4pm Friday for cash!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"Your call is OTM by $1 at 3:59pm on expiration Friday. What should you do?",options:["Hold it - maybe it goes ITM in the last minute","Let it expire worthless - not worth the effort","Exercise it anyway","Call your broker immediately"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Correct decision. OTM options are worthless. Selling it might get you $1-5, but after commissions, it's not worth it. Let it expire. Accept the loss. Move on to the next trade. This is part of options trading.",explanation_wrong:"With 1 minute left and OTM, your option is basically worthless. Yes, you could sell for $1-2, but after commissions you might net zero. Professional traders let these expire and focus on their next opportunity. Don't waste energy on pennies."},{screen_type:"summary_cards",headline:"Assignment & Exercise Rules",cards:[{front:"What do 95% of option traders do?",back:"SELL the option before expiration for cash. Never exercise, never get assigned. Treat options like trading cards - buy low, sell high, collect cash. Avoid the complexity of shares."},{front:"When does auto-exercise happen?",back:"If your option is ITM by $0.01+ at 4pm Friday, most brokers auto-exercise. Monday: you own shares (calls) or are short shares (puts). Avoid surprise: sell before 4pm or have cash ready."},{front:"Assignment risk - who has it?",back:"Only option SELLERS have assignment risk. If you only BUY options, you control when/if to exercise. You can't be assigned. This is why beginners should stick to buying initially."}]},{screen_type:"celebration",xp_earned:70,total_xp:740,badge:"üì¨ Assignment Expert",badge_description:"You'll never be surprised by assignment!",celebration_message:"Excellent! You now understand what happens at expiration. Next: calculating your max risk and reward before entering any trade.",streak_bonus:!1,next_lesson_preview:{title:"Max Loss vs Max Gain",description:"Learn to calculate your worst and best case scenarios BEFORE you trade",unlock_status:"unlocked"}}],r={lesson_id:e,title:o,estimated_time:t,screens:s};export{r as default,t as estimated_time,e as lesson_id,s as screens,o as title};
